		<!-- message -->
		<div>OK good discussion lets get started:<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt1" style="border:1px inset">
			
				I'm a chanter and I agree with you that nonchanter charm is too restrictive in LDoN
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
Not only are the charm options restricted to almost irrelevance.  They also made it so the Druids main method of Charm break protection (snare) does not work as all Charmable mobs are immune.  Not to discount the effect on Necros/Mages but these classes all have viable pets that somewhat mitigate the issue for them.  Even enchanter should be somewhat upset that this Tool has been taken from their Tool Kit and turned a little rusty.<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt1" style="border:1px inset">
			
				It's the only ability we have that scales. It's already limited in places of use, don't water it down to just another toy please.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
I agree that I do not wish to see charm even in it's current form diminished in any way but, just look at LDoN and you will see that Charm isn't just watered down it's drowning.  I certainly don't want to see the trend continue in GoD but, this is almost certain to continue if we accept a "no compromise" approach.<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt1" style="border:1px inset">
			
				What it does is show the imbalance already in the game...i.e. Mobflation.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
I agree that there is mobflation in the game.  As the player characters get more powerful the developers design increasingly hard apponents for them to confront.  This shouldn't surprise anyone.  I think what the fundamental problem that causes it to become unbalanced is that mobs are designed to individually challenge a party of 6 players and, in order to meet that challenge the developers design them based on 1 mob = 6 players.  Now you give one player the ability to harness this power and, you make 1 charming player > 6 players.  Now thats an over simplified way of stating but, it doesn't change the fact that there are a very real issues the developers are confronting when designing content to deal with players that can charm.  Don't get me wrong.  I like the feeling of power I have when I charm a mob and take out targets that even a whole group of people have a difficult time with.  I don't really relish the idea of the existing charm changing in any way but, faced with a situation like LDoN the question begs to be asked where is the middle ground.<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt1" style="border:1px inset">
			
				Additionally, when someone mentions 'The Charm Nerf', I really tend to forget exactly which one you are referring to. Some of them were good, and some of them were bad, it would help if you define which ones you are referring to.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
I am glad you asked this because I didn't fully address it in my inital post.  I have already written at length about the LDoN in essence Nerf of omission to charm (Lets not get into argument over "What is a Nerf").  Specifical for Druids the limited number of themes that have charmable mobs, the rareness of charmable mobs within those themes, and the inability to use the utility of snare to mitigate charm breaks.  As for Non-LDoN nerfs I believe shortly after Las Vegas Fan Faire last year all resist adjust were removed from charm effects.  I'm not a Lucy master like some people are but here is the entry for Command of Tunare:<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt1" style="border:1px inset">
			
				01-15 11:04 Changed Resistadj from -25 to 0 
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
As you know resist adjust is very important in determining the average duration of a charm spell.  That coupled with the Casting 8 sec and Recast timer 12 sec on CoT make charming infinitely more complicated.  Now add the no snare tag on top of that and you can see that there is a distressing trend here.  By way of comparision (not to troll enchanters here) Command of Druzzil level 64 Enchanter charm is a 5 sec cast time and 2.2 recast.  Their Resist adjust was also nerfed from -50 to 0 on the same patch.  The actual adjust to the resist is only half the story we all know mobs are getting increasingly hire resists as the players do also.  In LDoN even this has been aplified.  Have you ever tried to Root/Snare are a mob in LDoN and have it bounce 2,3 times in a row and, these spells have resist adjusts.<br />
<br />
I know I seem fixated on LDoN here but, I see that as a trend in SOEs attitude towards charm.  I do not want to see this trend continue in GoD.  When I first started playing Everquest I looked at all the classes before deciding what to play.  My first choice was Enchanter.  I admit I do have enchanter envy.  When I found that the enchanter class did not really fit my play style (mostly solo).  I search for one that did.  Druids at that time with Ports,SoW and the ability to Heal fit what I wanted to a T.  When I started my druid we had certain abilities.  One was the ability to Call upon the creatures of nature to be our allies and fight with us in our struggles to protect life.  I only wish to preserve this capability so that is both balanced and effective.</div>
