	</td>
	<td class="alt2">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>It seems to me that the current nerf is a compromise by SOE.<br />
<br />
Do you remember one of the versions of the charm nerf on test?  To my recollection, it was a 1% slow on all charm spells.  Very quickly the charm classes picked up on the fact that haste spells would be rendered useless with charmed pets.  This is especially true for Druids, since our haste spells are <i>only</i> useful for charmed pets (whereas Chanter haste is also good for players, Mage haste is still good for summoned pets).  Why make a spell lineup completely obsolete?<br />
<br />
If the LDoN nerf to Druids (that is, speaking from our point of view) was by ommision, then seems to me that a seperate unhastable line would be preferable to not having any charm options at all.<br />
<br />
My personal nerf suggestion <u>alternative</u> was to take out the 1% slow, and put level restrictions on our haste spells, plus add new haste spells that would work on the highest level charm.<br />
<br />
For example:<br />
Savage Spirit - Would work on level 46 and below (DC okay, but nothing higher): 70% haste, 45 Str, 16 AC.<br />
New spell - Would have lower haste (ie: 15 - 20%), less str and AC values, higher mana cost, but works on charms up to our level 60 animal pets.<br />
<br />
Then, add a few more animals in a lot more zones for us to charm.  Not being able to snare charmable pets in LDoN seems like a fair risk vs. reward, to be honest.  Although, each of the other classes has a mez for their charm types, whereas we don't.<br />
<br />
My main point is, yeah... our charm selection sucks.  If charm is too overpowered in the eyes of SOE to continue with this line as is <b>then fix it</b>.  There is plenty of ways to go about this while maintaining risk vs. reward.  Taking it away from us by putting so many restrictions on charm so that 95% of the time we don't even have the <i>choice</i> to use it is a very poor way to go about it, IMO.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
